Maybe because he=E2=80=99s from my hometown of Worcester, or maybe because =
we=E2=80=99re about the same age, or maybe because I grew up around the cor=
ner from Bob Cousy and have been a lifelong Celtics fan, I was absolutely e=
ntranced by Wycliffe =E2=80=9CWyc=E2=80=9D Grousbeck=E2=80=99s recent Zoom =
appearance, alongside hedge fund manager Lee Ainslie, at the Economic Club =
of New York the other week. Grousbeck, of course, is the principal owner an=
d governor of the Celtics, the reigning NBA championship franchise that he =
purchased, along with a group of his rich friends=E2=80=94including his bil=
lionaire father, Irv, a co-founder of Continental Cablevision=E2=80=94for $=
360 million in 2002. During his 22 years of ownership, the Celtics have won=
 two NBA rings, adding to the record 18 NBA championships the franchise has=
 won over the years.

After winning the
title this past spring, Grousbeck and his partners put the team up for sale=
, hiring Gregg Lemkau, at BDT & MSD Partners, and Mary Erdoes, at JPMorgan =
Chase, to run the process. It=E2=80=99s expected to fetch a boffo price of =
around $6 billion, one-third more than the $4 billion that Mat Ishbia, the =
billionaire mortgage maven, paid for the Phoenix Suns in 2022. I can=E2=80=
=99t do the I.R.R. calculation anymore, but I can figure out that he and hi=
s partners will likely make close to 30 times their equity investment in th=
e deal. That=E2=80=99s pretty damn impressive, and might be more than what =
Josh Harris and his posse will make on their roughly $260 million purchase =
of the Philadelphia 76ers=E2=80=94$135 million of equity and $125 million o=
f debt from the NBA=E2=80=94in 2011, should they decide to sell.

Grousbeck said he was selling the team for estate-planning reasons, leaving=
 many fans and observers quietly stunned. Why would a
billionaire sell a team right on the heels of a championship, especially wi=
th a nucleus of young talent and coaches in place? Yes, 22 years is a long =
time for a bunch of L.B.O. guys to own anything. But perhaps the better rea=
son is because Grousbeck isn=E2=80=99t a typical owner=E2=80=94he came abou=
t the Celtics in an unusual way, and has an innate sense of both how to run=
 a team and when to trade one.

The Grousbeck story is, well, engrossing. After prep school, he was off to =
Princeton, where he was a history major and a member of the 1983 lightweigh=
t crew team that won the Ivy League and national titles. After Princeton, a=
nd a law degree from the University of Michigan and an MBA from Stanford, h=
e joined the Cambridge-based V.C. firm Highland Capital Partners. But at 41=
, after seven years of sitting at a desk, writing one venture-capital check=
 after another, Wyc had a midlife crisis of sorts and made a cold call that=
 turned into perhaps the greatest leveraged buyout in sports
history.

The Gaston Call

It was the early 2000s, and Wyc was starting to think about what he really =
wanted to do with his life. One day, he looked up at the wall of his office=
 and saw a picture of himself and his Princeton lightweight crew teammates =
who=E2=80=99d won that 1983 national title, and it dawned on him. =E2=80=9C=
I liked being that person,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cbeing in a boat and b=
eing accountable for how much work I put in and how we did as a boat. I lov=
ed the team concept. I suddenly realized that was, in a way of saying it, t=
he me I wanted to be. I wanted to be that person again, competing on a team=
, not solely. I don=E2=80=99t have the talent to be by myself anyway, but [=
I loved] being on a team and going for the whole thing.=E2=80=9D

He decided he needed to buy a Boston sports team and to try to win a champi=
onship. At the time, he wasn=E2=80=99t thinking it would be a great
investment. He didn=E2=80=99t even have much money=E2=80=94just the chutzpa=
h to think he could get the money he needed. =E2=80=9CI just wanted to do i=
t for the love of it,=E2=80=9D he said. He had recently been to a Celtics g=
ame and noticed that the stands were half-empty, which he didn=E2=80=99t th=
ink was right for such a storied franchise. On a whim, he called up Paul Ga=
ston, the principal owner of the Celtics=E2=80=94which at the time was a ra=
re publicly traded partnership, listed on the N.Y.S.E.=E2=80=94and made an =
appointment to see him at his office in New York.

At their meeting, Wyc asked Gaston what he wanted for the team, for which t=
he Gaston family had paid around $20 million (not a typo) in 1983. After a =
little back and forth, he asked Gaston to name his fantasy price. Gaston sp=
it out a big, wild number: $360 million, some 18 times what the family had =
paid nearly two decades before. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m very clear,=E2=80=9D h=
e recalled at the Economic Club of New York. =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t have=
 the
money myself, not even close. But there was cash flow there. I thought mayb=
e I could do an L.B.O. I=E2=80=99d never done one of those before, but I th=
ought I could get up to a certain number, maybe make the numbers all work. =
=E2=80=A6 And he named that number.=E2=80=9D

Wyc told Gaston he had a deal. He didn=E2=80=99t negotiate, even though it =
would mean paying the highest price ever for an NBA franchise to that point=
=2E He explained to Gaston that he d=
idn=E2=80=99t have the money, but that he=
 would get it by the end of the year, three and a half months later. He als=
o promised to immediately wire Gaston a nonrefundable down payment on the $=
360 million purchase price. =E2=80=9CI'll give you the rest December 31, bu=
t either way, you keep the deposit,=E2=80=9D he told Gaston. He mortgaged h=
is house, pulled together some other money he had around, and wired the dep=
osit to Gaston.

Dialing for Dollars

Wyc started rolling calls. He got three noes in a row from three Boston bil=
lionaires, and started to second-guess himself. But then he began to genera=
te some interest. There was Steve Pagliuca, from Bain Capital, along with a=
 few of his Bain partners, as well as the likes of Glenn Hutchins and David=
 Roux, two of the co-founders of Silver Lake Partners, and David Bonderman,=
 the co-founder of TPG. (Usual disclosure: TPG is an investor in Puck).

By the end, he=E2=80=99d gathered 25 partners in a deal comprising $200 mil=
lion of equity and $160 million of borrowed money. =E2=80=9CI lost 17 pound=
s raising this money,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt was like lightweight cr=
ew all over again; I was cutting weight. But I was nervous. I was excited. =
I couldn=E2=80=99t eat or sleep, I couldn=E2=80=99t do anything but get the=
 deal done.=E2=80=9D (Pagliuca is rumored
to be a leading candidate to buy the Celtics from Grousbeck and seems to ha=
ve a pole position, given that he=E2=80=99s already one of the team=E2=80=
=99s biggest owners, with a roughly 20 percent stake. He=E2=80=99s hired bo=
th Allen & Co. and The Raine Group to advise him.)

Even though his partnership group contained several I.R.R.-hungry masters o=
f the universe, Grousbeck said they were willing to think differently about=
 owning the Celtics. And there was never a second capital call. =E2=80=9CEv=
ery single person came in and thought about it as the emotional satisfactio=
n of being part of something bigger than ourselves,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=
=80=9CWe made that clear to everybody. I said, =E2=80=98We=E2=80=99re proba=
bly overpaying. We=E2=80=99re going to be paid in enjoyment,=E2=80=99 was m=
y phrase at the time. =E2=80=98This is the last Boston team I think that=E2=
=80=99s going to sell in our lifetimes. And imagine if we win? I think we c=
an be competitive and not go totally broke. If there=E2=80=99s ever any ext=
ra money lying around, we=E2=80=99re going
to put it into the team and try to make the team better. Having said that, =
if there=E2=80=99s ever really extra money around, we=E2=80=99ll all share =
it out equally.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D

There were no puts. There were no hurdle rates. There was no preferred stoc=
k. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re all in it, really together,=E2=80=9D he told his =
new partners. =E2=80=9CEverybody came in for love. They=E2=80=99re all grea=
t business people, but they came in for love and passion, and then it has w=
orked out better than we even thought.=E2=80=9D

Grousbeck and his partners completed the purchase on New Year=E2=80=99s Eve=
, 2002. They retained the legendary Red Auerbach=E2=80=94who had been reapp=
ointed team president in late 2001=E2=80=94as a link to the once-great Celt=
ics teams of past eras; hired Danny Ainge as G.M. and Doc Rivers as coach; =
and masterminded the trades that landed Kevin Garnett and Ray Allen to play=
 beside Paul Pierce in his prime=E2=80=94the first real Big Three concept o=
f the modern
era. In 2008, of course, that team brought the Larry O=E2=80=99Brien Trophy=
 back to Boston for the first time since 1986. Then in June, behind a talen=
ted young core led by Jason Tatum and Jaylen Brown, Joe Mazzulla won the NB=
A title in his only second season, one of the youngest coaches to ever win =
a championship. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve had great people running the basketb=
all side and great players and great fans,=E2=80=9D Grousbeck said. =E2=80=
=9CIt=E2=80=99s all been a really amazing ride.=E2=80=9D

Ainslie wanted to know what advice Grousbeck had for other current or aspir=
ing team owners. Grousbeck is also a part owner of Cincoro Tequila, along w=
ith his wife and several other NBA team owners, including Michael Jordan, J=
eanie Buss, and Wes Edens. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re not asking me for advic=
e, but we all share insights,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s put =
it this way: Wes would rather die than ask me for advice. That=E2=80=99s ho=
w good he is.=E2=80=9D First, he said, you can=E2=80=99t run a team to
maximize profits. =E2=80=9CThe fans will figure it out,=E2=80=9D he said. =
=E2=80=9CPlayers will figure it out. You shouldn=E2=80=99t do it. You shoul=
d be lucky enough to be able to run these for love, and then you probably w=
ill not go broke.=E2=80=9D

Grousbeck said he was probably the =E2=80=9Cleast well-capitalized owner=E2=
=80=9D in the NBA, =E2=80=9Cbut we=E2=80=99ve been successful because we pu=
t the money into the team. We=E2=80=99re not better than anybody else.=E2=
=80=9D So long as the owners have a passion for the team, =E2=80=9Ceverythi=
ng will work out fine, but not the other way around.=E2=80=9D If you are tr=
ying to decide between owning a sports team or owning Nvidia, he joked, =E2=
=80=9Cstick to the stock market,=E2=80=9D he said.

Finally, he showed off to the Zoom audience the massive 2024 championship r=
ing that the team=E2=80=99s owners and players received. The top of the rin=
g comes off to display a miniature championship banner and piece of the Cel=
tics parquet floor.

Now, Grousbeck et al. are all just waiting for the
team to be sold. And, no, he said, he doesn=E2=80=99t have a number in mind=
, assuming there=E2=80=99s someone out there who has the guts to ask him.

From the Cheap Seats

On ESPN=E2=80=99s trade of Big 12 games for =E2=80=98Inside the NBA=E2=80=
=99: =E2=80=9CThe reader comments about the ESPN deal strike me as both stu=
pid and jealous. How many live games does ESPN have?! A few Big 12 games in=
 exchange for Inside the NBA? Are you kidding me?! And does the person who =
commented on Charles=E2=80=99 commentary being a potential problem not know=
 McAfee is on ESPN every damn day?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A former ESPNer

