x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Wyc started rolling=
 calls. He got three noes in a row from three Boston billionaires, and star=
ted to second-guess himself. But then he began to generate some interest. T=
here was <b>Steve Pagliuca</b>, from Bain Capital, along with a few of his =
Bain partners, as well as the likes of <b>Glenn Hutchins </b>and <b>David R=
oux</b>, two of the co-founders of Silver Lake Partners, and <b>David Bonde=
rman</b>, the co-founder of TPG. (Usual disclosure: TPG is an investor in P=
uck). <br/><br/>By the end, he=E2=80=99d gathered 25 partners in a deal com=
prising $200 million of equity and $160 million of borrowed money. =E2=80=
=9CI lost 17 pounds raising this money,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt was l=
ike lightweight crew all over again; I was cutting weight. But I was nervou=
s. I was excited. I couldn=E2=80=99t eat or sleep, I couldn=E2=80=99t do an=
ything but get the deal done.=E2=80=9D (Pagliuca is rumored
to be a leading candidate to buy the Celtics from Grousbeck and seems to ha=
ve a pole position, given that he=E2=80=99s already one of the team=E2=80=
=99s biggest owners, with a roughly 20 percent stake. He=E2=80=99s hired bo=
th Allen &amp; Co. and The Raine Group to advise him.)<br/><br/>Even though=
 his partnership group contained several I.R.R.-hungry masters of the unive=
rse, Grousbeck said they were willing to think differently about owning the=
 Celtics. And there was never a second capital call. =E2=80=9CEvery single =
person came in and thought about it as the emotional satisfaction of being =
part of something bigger than ourselves,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CWe made=
 that clear to everybody. I said, =E2=80=98We=E2=80=99re probably overpayin=
g. We=E2=80=99re going to be paid in enjoyment,=E2=80=99 was my phrase at t=
he time. =E2=80=98This is the last Boston team I think that=E2=80=99s going=
 to sell in our lifetimes. And imagine if we win? I think we can be competi=
tive and not go totally broke. If there=E2=80=99s ever any extra money lyin=
g around, we=E2=80=99re going
to put it into the team and try to make the team better. Having said that, =
if there=E2=80=99s ever <i>really</i> extra money around, we=E2=80=99ll all=
 share it out equally.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>There were no puts. Ther=
e were no hurdle rates. There was no preferred stock. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99r=
e all in it, really together,=E2=80=9D he told his new partners. =E2=80=9CE=
verybody came in for love. They=E2=80=99re all great business people, but t=
hey came in for love and passion, and then it has worked out better than we=
 even thought.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Grousbeck and his partners completed the p=
urchase on New Year=E2=80=99s Eve, 2002. They retained the legendary <b>Red=
 Auerbach</b>=E2=80=94who had been reappointed team president in late 2001=
=E2=80=94as a link to the once-great Celtics teams of past eras; hired <b>D=
anny Ainge</b> as G.M. and <b>Doc Rivers</b> as coach; and masterminded the=
 trades that landed <b>Kevin Garnett </b>and <b>Ray Allen </b>to play besid=
e <b>Paul Pierce </b>in his prime=E2=80=94the first real <i>Big Three </i>c=
oncept of the modern
era. In 2008, of course, that team brought the Larry O=E2=80=99Brien Trophy=
 back to Boston for the first time since 1986. Then in June, behind a talen=
ted young core led by <b>Jason Tatum</b> and <b>Jaylen Brown</b>, <b>Joe Ma=
zzulla</b> won the NBA title in his only second season, one of the youngest=
 coaches to ever win a championship. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve had great peopl=
e running the basketball side and great players and great fans,=E2=80=9D Gr=
ousbeck said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s all been a really amazing ride.=E2=80=
=9D<br/><br/>Ainslie wanted to know what advice Grousbeck had for other cur=
rent or aspiring team owners. Grousbeck is also a part owner of Cincoro Teq=
uila, along with his wife and several other NBA team owners, including <b>M=
ichael Jordan</b>, <b>Jeanie Buss</b>, and <b>Wes Edens</b>. =E2=80=9CThey=
=E2=80=99re not asking me for advice, but we all share insights,=E2=80=9D h=
e said. =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s put it this way: Wes would rather die than a=
sk me for advice. That=E2=80=99s how good he is.=E2=80=9D First, he said, y=
ou can=E2=80=99t run a team to
maximize profits. =E2=80=9CThe fans will figure it out,=E2=80=9D he said. =
=E2=80=9CPlayers will figure it out. You shouldn=E2=80=99t do it. You shoul=
d be lucky enough to be able to run these for love, and then you probably w=
ill not go broke.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Grousbeck said he was probably the =E2=
=80=9Cleast well-capitalized owner=E2=80=9D in the NBA, =E2=80=9Cbut we=E2=
=80=99ve been successful because we put the money into the team. We=E2=80=
=99re not better than anybody else.=E2=80=9D So long as the owners have a p=
assion for the team, =E2=80=9Ceverything will work out fine, but not the ot=
her way around.=E2=80=9D If you are trying to decide between owning a sport=
s team or owning Nvidia, he joked, =E2=80=9Cstick to the stock market,=E2=
=80=9D he said.<br/><br/>Finally, he showed off to the Zoom audience the ma=
ssive 2024 championship ring that the team=E2=80=99s owners and players rec=
eived. The top of the ring comes off to display a miniature championship ba=
nner and piece of the Celtics parquet floor. <br/><br/>Now, Grousbeck <i>et=
 al</i>. are all just waiting for the
team to be sold. And, no, he said, he doesn=E2=80=99t have a number in mind=
, assuming there=E2=80=99s someone out there who has the guts to ask him.<b=
r/></td>
